@node "Features" "Features"

Features
--------

GuideTool has the following features:

- is able to create tables of contents, index files and cross refs automatically

- cross refs or link labels can be included automatically in an AG File

- Creates his special output files (for table of contents and cros references)
  in ASCII format and can be changed with any text editor.
  
- external files also saves you from scanning a AG file for nodes or link labels
  if you change it often.

- index files will be sorted automatically in alphabetic order

- source code included to serve as an example for writing an Amiga application

@endnode

@node "Installation" "How to install the program"

Installation
------------

I haven't included an Installer Skript for installing the program, because it
is unnecessary with only two important files. Simply copy the Guide-File in
your prefered language to the preferred doc directory (f.e.: HELP:English) and
the binary to a directory in your path (recommendation: sys:tools).

Moreover I've included the automatically created Contents and Xref files for
the GuideTool Guide. These should serve as an example and don't need to be
installed. By the way the "raw" version of the Guide file (without cross ref-
erences) is called GuideTool.guide.orig.


@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

Requirements
------------

GuideTool needs the following requirement to work:

- An Amiga with at least 512 KB RAM (it should work, never testet it though)

- OS2.04 or better (I myself haven't tested it with OS2.04, because I only can
  use OS3.1, but I didn't use any 3.1 Features.)

- AmigaGuide Files and of course the AmigaGuide Tool itself (for OS2.04 ava-
  laible from Aminet or Fred Fish Library Services Fish 920, for OS3.x Users
  usable with the Multiview program)

@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

GuideTool 1.0 Copyright (C) 1995 by Reinhard Katzmann. All Rights Reserved
Usage: GuideTool FROM/A,TO/A,C=CONTENTFILE/K,X=XREFFILE/K,CONTENTS/S,INDEX/S,
                 XREF/S,MAKECONT/S,MAKEXREF/S,L=LABELSIZE/K/N,R=XREFSIZE/K/N,ILN=INNERLINKS/S

This is the usage synopsis. You have to specify at least the input file (FROM),
the output file (TO) and one (exclusively one) of the switsches /s. With cer-
tain switches you must also specify a Content or a Xref file.

The input and the output file must differ (the program checks this) must also
differ from the Content/Xref file.

The input and output files have different significations dependant from the switch.

Detailed explanation of the Synopsis:

FROM: Input file: Usually this is the Amigaguide file you want to work on.
      Exception: INDEX, there it is the xref (= cross reference)) file being
      created with the MAKEXREF switch or by hand.

TO: Output file: Dependant from the switch you choose this is the contentfile,
    the xreffile or the indexfile being written as AG index file or AG contents
    file or being the AG file written with link labels. (Given in the order of
    the Synopsis)

Remark: All created files are saved in the ASCII format. Consequently you can
        edit it with an text editor.

Warning: the program supports Amigaguide files with a line length up to 255
         characters. There are some less checks for that, but I can give no
         warranty that the program runs still stable if the length exceeds
         255 characters.

C=CONTENTFILE/K: contents file for reading using the switch CONTENTS. The look
                 of this file is explained in an extra section.

X=XREFFILE/K: xref file for reading using the switch XREF or INDEX. The look of
              this file is explained in an extra section.

Switches: Only _ONE_ switch may be used at the same time.

CONTENTS/S: Saves the AG table of contents with the help of a contents file
            (as main node). This can then be included in the own AG file with
            the help of an text editor.
            
XREF/S: Save the AG File with all link labels with the help of a xref File
        and what could be found with the help of the search function. The 
        function is not too fast and her functionality is explained in the
        extern file XREF-Konzept more detailed. XREF includes no link labels
        in the main node and in the node which is identical with the link 
        label. (the last will be probably changeable in the future at wish).

INDEX/S: Saves an AG index file  with the help of an INDEX file. This can then
         be added in the own AG file with the help of a text editor. I recom-
         mand to put it at the end of the file. Moreover i recommand to make
         an additonial entry into the table of contents.

MAKECONT/S: Creates Contents file file which is saved in the ASCII format. It can
            then be edited with an text editor. All node commands are read from
            the AG file (\@node) and the node names as well as the labels are
            saved. If you don't want to include a specific node, simply include
            in the node a \@rem ignorenode. Example:

     \@node "Foo" "Bar"
     \@rem ignorenode

MAKEXREF/S: Creates XRef file which is saved in the ASCII format. It can
            then be edited with an text editor. All link labels of the follow-
            ing kind are being read from the AG file:
            \@{"<label>" link "<node>"}. The program checks for doubled labels.
            More commands are not (yet) supported at the moment.

L=LABELSIZE/K/N: The maximum size of a link label. Defaults to 60.
                 You can change the string size of a link label with this 
                 option (indifferent if \@Node or \@{".." link ".."} is used).
                 Warning: Too small values can lead to fatal errors!!

R=XREFSIZE/K/N: The maximum size of a cross reference. Defaults to 40.
                You can change the string size of a reference with this option
                (indifferent if \@Node or \@{".." link ".."} is used). Warning:
                Too small values can lead to fatal errors!!

ILN=INNERLINKS/S: Switch which enables that links with the same name but diff-
                  erent jump number are accepted. With that you can use the
                  possibility of AmigaGuide to jump within a node better be-
                  cause it also allows you to add a link in a node with the
                  same name as the node itself (if the jump goes not to 0).

If there are any other problems, try to increase your stack size to around
10 - 20 kb.

How to proceed
--------------

Here some tips how you could create an Amigaguide file.

First you should create an AG file as usual. You should omit main node, index
and cross references, because this is what the program takes over. 

Then you should make a node, where are listed all cross references you want to
have. These will be exploited by the program. If you want to spare the time to
fill in all the labels by hand you also can create the Xref file by hand. (Even
in a GUI version, this hard part can't be taken from you - ideas welcome :-)
Otherwise you create the Xref file after that.

Thereupon you should create an index file for the AG file with the help of the
created Xref file.  You should also lay hand on the file because generally there
are undesired cross references in the AG file (provided that you have already
included some, I dissuade you from creating all automatically.) The Index file
is then appended to the AG file (with an text editor or with join :). This file
created so far will then be treated farther.

Now you create the table of contents. Like before you should also here process
the created file with a text editor. A future GUI will make things easier here,
too. If you have the Contents file, you can include the main node and with that
the table of contents to the AG file. You should create the table of contents
after the index because you don't need then to create an extra Index entry into
the table of contents.

Last you can include to this created file all cross references with the help of
the XREF option. If the file is bigger, you can now drink a cup of coffee (or
tea which is my preference ;-). But don't pour the coffee over the keyboard!


@endnode

@node "ExtFiles" "External files"

External Files
--------------

Following is the description of the files which are created using NAKEXREF and
MAKECONT. In both files you can insert a comment using ";", which is ignored
by the program.

The contents file consists of two parts being separated by a line where "###"
stands in (You may not forget this!) The upper part is completely ignored by
the program and will be taken over as it comes. After that the program writes
"Table of Contents" appending two empty lines. Thereupon the upper part will
be inserted. Subsequently the Contents file is given out as link labels in the
same order as found in the file. Every line in the lower part looks like this:

<reference> <label> <any text>

label is the text which you can see on the screen and the reference is the node
to which will be jumped if you select the label. The label has to have always
quotes and the reference should usually have them, too. Pay attention to not
forget the blank between the label and the reference! Behind the reference 
after another blank can be any text which will be appended after the AG label.

The xref file consists - similar to the contents file - of labels and referen-
ces. The program reads the file and searches every line for agreement with the
labels as you can look up in the external XREF-Concept. If it finds an agree-
ment it checks if the reference is identical with the node. If not, the label
will be included as AG reference in the current text line.

<label> <reference> <line number>

Label and reference have the same meaning as before. However a reference comes
usually several times in contrast to the table of contents. The line number
specifies to which text place should be jumped (relative to the beginning of
the node). For more information please read the Amigaguide Doc file.
While creating a file it is in any case reasonable to make use of the line
number declaration. (in fact I saw it as good as never). By the way is to 
mention that the labels are sorted when using the XREF switch for beeing
able to use a faster searching method. If you should have several same labels
the program with different references the program will take the first which
it encounters and ignores the rest. If you should have a better idea, please
contact me.


@endnode

@node "MakeGuide" "MakeGuide - ARexx programm to simplify GuideTool"

Makeguide.rexx is written by Ralf Sponnier. Makeguide.rexx is able to get one
file name as argument. If you omit it, it opens an file requester and requests
a file (no more check afterwards). It creates an contents file with the help
of GuideTool and adds it as "main" node to the Guide or adds it to the main
node if one does already exist. After that it creates an xref-file and this
will be applied to the guide. At the end you have your original guide and
<filename.guide.new> as result. Intermediate files will be deleted if you
don't break makeguide.

Makeguide.rexx can be found in the ARexx directory.

The program will get obsolete with the GUI version of GuideTool.

@endnode

@node "Bugs_Ideas" "Bugs and Ideas"

Bugs
----

There's hardly any program which has not some bugs. So I don't pretend that
mine would have none. But I try to get the program as stable as possible on 
all the different computer systems which meet the requirements. Just with this
program it may give bugs which are features (i,e, I wanted it to have that way)
You can certainly discuss these "bugs" with me but I keep the last word.

Known bugs
----------

- program is relative slow in XREF mode. I have included the concept of the
  XREF function, in case anyone has a great idea, how to speed up the function.
  (I have tgought about it a lot and made some improvements on the way, but
  ideas are always welcome :-)

- Since Version 0.8 only "whole words" are recognized (words are separated
  by certain Symbolt: "\t\n !\"#$&\',-./:;=?@`"). Hence partial words are no
  longer recognized (perhabs I may include an option therefore in the future,
  in any case partial word parsing is very slow)

- The program does not check if the AG file is correct. In case commands have
  any errors and the program gets into an edless loop, don't accuse me! :-)

- Does _not_ recognize nodes which consist of reference only, Exception:
  \@node main (more precisely: No warranty how the program behaves in it)

- Don't wonder about the many links in the file. I've created it with GuideTool
  without revision so you get a bit of a feeling, where to add them by hand.

- MAKEXREF does not recognize \@{ as comment

- the index of this guide seems to crash amigaguide :-( Any hints are welcomed!

Bug reports and Ideas
---------------------

If you find a bug or have an idea, how to improve the program, don't heitate
to tell it to me. There's only one restriction: It's not on my mind to make
an AG creation tool out of my program like Heddley (Though I did not find a
similar program which would have convinced me using it). Before you start to
suggest me any ideas or extensions please read the section about the future
of the program.

Of course bugs are handled in preference to the ideas and I also try to get
rid of them as fast as my spare time allows. But still I'll collect all ideas
and endeavour after answering all mail. You can reach me through my address.

@endnode

@node "Future" "Future Development of the program"

With Version 1.0 I complete the development of the CLI-Version (i.e. there
will be BUGfixes at most. From now on I develop the GUI Version (rough ideas
l. below, a concept is in the work). The development being quite complex I
will need some time until the first beta version will be avalaible to the
beta testers. If there is enough interest I can distribute the concept
publically (posting to news groups).

Here are a few ideas I might implement (no special order):

- Speed improvement of XREF function as far as possible

- Perhabs a change of the MAKEXREF output file to get a compatibility with the
  XREF files of the original AmigaGuide AD2AG utility.

- Consequently perhabs a change of the MAKECONT output file

- Possibility, to change line numbers "on the fly" on XREF output
  (I ask myself how I imagined to do that ;-)

- Possibility, to specify a list of links which will be ignored or perhabs
  even can be deleted (much easier within a GUI Version ;-)

- Prefs file: For the above options. Probably not before the GUI version.

- GUI with help of BGUI, this would be a second program practically:

  * Two - three listview gadgets for table of contents and link labels
  * String Gadgets for the different in/output files incl. file requester
  * Perhabs possibility to change the number of nodes/link labels
  * Status information gadget
  * Progress gadget which shows how far the function has proceeded
  * possibility to remove certain link labels for the index
  * delete, change and add, sort labels
  * possibility to remove links for XREFing (perhabs even disable for certain
    nodes)
  * more ideas from you :-)

Ideas by other people
---------------------

- Word Wrapping: Useable with the help of a switch. My current concept to this
  seems to make quite an overhead IMO. Word Wrapping is testing if a word has 
  been wrappeded in a line while I have to keep track globally of the word.
  (idea originates from Magnus) - opinions ? (Concept has been added)

- switch to append respectively insert the output directly at the original
  AG file (CONTENTS and INDEX switch) (obsolete with Makeguide.rexx)

- ARexx Port (not before GUI version) to be able to control the tool
  in another way.

- Connected with it: Perhabs i'll make a commodity out og GuideTool so the
  window has not to be open all the time etc. (from me).

@endnode

